7
00:00:50,187 --> 00:00:51,437
Story of the Week.

8
00:00:51,437 --> 00:00:56,312
OpenAI AI Disproves 80-Year-Old Mathematics — And This Time It's Real.

9
00:00:56,312 --> 00:01:05,850
For nearly 80 years, mathematicians considered it settled that square lattice arrangements represented the optimal solution to the Erdős Unit Distance Problem.

10
00:01:05,850 --> 00:01:11,625
On May 20, 2026, an OpenAI reasoning model proved that assumption wrong .

11
00:01:11,625 --> 00:01:21,062
The Erdős Unit Distance Problem, posed in 1946, asks: how many point pairs in a set of n points can share exactly the same distance?

12
00:01:21,062 --> 00:01:31,975
The model found new geometric constructions that systematically outperform classical lattice arrangements — through an unexpected connection between combinatorics and algebraic number theory .

13
00:01:31,975 --> 00:01:40,062
OpenAI describes it as "the first time AI has autonomously solved a prominent open problem central to a field of mathematics" .

14
00:01:40,062 --> 00:01:46,037
"AI is helping us to more fully explore the cathedral of mathematics we have built over the centuries."

15
00:01:46,037 --> 00:01:49,062
— Thomas Bloom, Erdős Problems Website

16
00:01:49,062 --> 00:02:01,875
What sets this announcement apart from previous ones: three independent top mathematicians externally verified the solution — Noga Alon, Melanie Wood, and Thomas Bloom (who also serves as the quote source) .

17
00:02:01,875 --> 00:02:16,912
This is a deliberate contrast to the October 2025 debacle, when OpenAI exec Kevin Weil claimed GPT-5 had solved ten Erdős problems — a claim that proved baseless and damaged trust in AI research announcements .

18
00:02:16,912 --> 00:02:17,925
Who should care?

19
00:02:17,925 --> 00:02:33,025
Anyone using or planning to use AI as a research tool: the breakthrough shows that AI models can not only verify existing proofs but find genuinely new mathematical constructions — using approaches humans hadn't discovered in 80 years.

20
00:02:33,025 --> 00:02:39,125
This has direct implications for cryptography, algorithm design, and theoretical computer science.

21
00:02:39,125 --> 00:02:45,125
Critical context: OpenAI has shown transparency problems with previous research claims.

22
00:02:45,125 --> 00:02:51,050
External peer review by at least three mathematicians is the decisive quality marker this time.

23
00:02:51,050 --> 00:03:01,362
Open questions remain about how far the model's reasoning extends beyond the specific task and what this tells us about transfer capabilities to other mathematical domains.

24
00:03:01,362 --> 00:03:11,512
Bottom line: An AI model has autonomously solved an open mathematical problem for the first time — verified, reproducible, 80 years after Erdős.

25
00:03:11,512 --> 00:03:12,850
More Top Stories.

26
00:03:12,850 --> 00:03:21,387
Anthropic Project Glasswing: 10,000+ Vulnerabilities — And That's Just the Beginning (Company Announcement).

27
00:03:21,387 --> 00:03:24,950
The bottleneck in software security has fundamentally shifted.

28
00:03:24,950 --> 00:03:38,787
Anthropic's Project Glasswing, deploying Claude Mythos Preview together with around 50 partner organizations, identified over 10,000 highly critical security vulnerabilities in its first weeks, according to Anthropic .

29
00:03:38,787 --> 00:03:47,462
In over 1,000 open-source projects alone, the system found 6,202 critical vulnerabilities per Anthropic's report.

30
00:03:47,462 --> 00:03:57,375
90.6% of AI-found vulnerabilities were externally confirmed as valid, with 62.4% rated as high or critical severity .

31
00:03:57,375 --> 00:04:15,987
For context: classical static analysis tools (SAST) typically validate only 10–30% of their findings as genuine vulnerabilities — the reported rate of 90.6% would be a significant improvement, though this comparison figure does not come from the Anthropic report itself.

32
00:04:16,912 --> 00:04:33,175
Numbers from individual partners are impressive: Cloudflare discovered 2,000 bugs (400 of them critical or high severity) per the report; Mozilla found 271 vulnerabilities in Firefox 150 — ten times more than in previous testing .

33
00:04:33,175 --> 00:04:41,675
The UK AI Security Institute confirmed Mythos Preview as the first model ever to fully solve both of their cyber simulations .

34
00:04:41,675 --> 00:04:44,675
Anthropic articulates the new problem clearly:.

35
00:04:44,675 --> 00:04:51,112
"Progress on software security is now limited by how quickly we can verify, disclose, and patch."

36
00:04:51,112 --> 00:05:01,125
Of 10,000+ vulnerabilities found, only 75 patches are available so far, with an average patching time of around two weeks .

37
00:05:01,125 --> 00:05:13,150
Bottom line: AI has democratized and scaled vulnerability discovery — the next critical challenge is whether human patch capacity can keep up before attackers exploit published findings.

38
00:05:13,150 --> 00:05:20,200
Google I/O 2026: Everything Becomes AI — And the Search Bar Looks New After 25 Years.

39
00:05:20,200 --> 00:05:29,712
Google delivered a week of announcements at I/O 2026 that together paint a clear picture: the entire product portfolio is being rebuilt AI-first .

40
00:05:29,712 --> 00:05:40,987
Gemini 3.5 Flash outperforms Gemini 3.1 Pro on coding and agent benchmarks (76.2% on Terminal-Bench 2.1) — at lower cost .

41
00:05:40,987 --> 00:05:52,137
Note: all cited benchmark figures compare Gemini models against each other; comparisons against Anthropic's Claude or OpenAI's models are absent from Google's official communications.

42
00:05:52,137 --> 00:06:07,725
More relevant for developers is Google Antigravity: a new agent-first development platform with a desktop app, CLI, and SDK for multi-agent orchestration, directly competing with Anthropic's Claude SDK and OpenAI's Agents platform .

43
00:06:07,725 --> 00:06:14,512
AI Mode in Google Search has surpassed one billion monthly users, with queries doubling every quarter .

44
00:06:14,512 --> 00:06:23,087
The new search bar accepts image, video, and file uploads for the first time — the first fundamental redesign in over 25 years  .

45
00:06:23,087 --> 00:06:31,200
All generated content receives imperceptible SynthID watermarks, which have been verified 50 million times globally to date .

46
00:06:31,200 --> 00:06:38,950
Android XR glasses in partnership with Gentle Monster, Warby Parker, and Samsung are slated for fall 2026 .

47
00:06:38,950 --> 00:06:49,925
Bottom line: Google demonstrates that the battle for the AI platform won't be decided by model benchmarks alone — but by integration into existing products with a billion users.

48
00:06:49,925 --> 00:06:56,162
Spotify + Universal Music: AI Covers Now Legal — With Consent and Revenue Share.

49
00:06:56,162 --> 00:07:11,700
The first major label-streaming licensing deal for AI-generated music has arrived: Spotify and Universal Music Group have agreed to allow fans to officially create AI covers and remixes of UMG artists — as a paid add-on for Spotify Premium .

50
00:07:11,700 --> 00:07:19,600
Participating artists receive a revenue share; participation is based on their explicit consent ("Artist-First" approach) .

51
00:07:19,600 --> 00:07:24,987
"What we're building is grounded in consent, credit, and compensation for the artists."

52
00:07:24,987 --> 00:07:26,637
— Spotify Co-CEO

53
00:07:26,637 --> 00:07:35,812
The contrast with Suno and Udio is intentional: instead of litigation over existing catalogs, this model relies on upfront agreements .

54
00:07:35,812 --> 00:07:42,575
UMG is the world's largest music label — whatever standard is set here will influence the entire industry.

55
00:07:42,575 --> 00:07:46,650
The add-on's price and specific launch date have not yet been announced .

56
00:07:46,650 --> 00:07:56,637
Critical voices come from indie artists and professional associations like the UK Musicians' Union: the consent model only applies to artists contracted with UMG.

57
00:07:56,637 --> 00:08:06,100
Independent musicians and smaller labels are left out — facing a choice of signing similar deals or fighting against a new de-facto industry practice.

58
00:08:06,100 --> 00:08:19,112
Bottom line: The music industry has found a workable path to monetize AI creativity without bypassing artists — a model that puts pressure on other labels but leaves important questions open for indie artists.

