00:09:05,400 --> 00:09:06,525
Tool of the Week.

65
00:09:06,525 --> 00:09:13,037
NVIDIA Nemotron-Labs Diffusion — Text generation in parallel blocks instead of token by token.

66
00:09:13,037 --> 00:09:26,725
While all other LLMs output text sequentially, NVIDIA's new Diffusion Language Models (DLM) generate 32 tokens simultaneously — achieving a 6.4× speedup over standard autoregression .

67
00:09:26,725 --> 00:09:34,650
On NVIDIA B200, that's ~865 tokens/second (4× faster than the autoregressive baseline) .

68
00:09:34,650 --> 00:09:44,812
What's special: a single model supports three modes without code changes — autoregressive (classic), diffusion (blocks), and self-speculation (hybrid) .

69
00:09:44,812 --> 00:09:47,200
NVIDIA describes the key advantage:.

70
00:09:47,200 --> 00:09:58,300
"Not only can these models better leverage the computational model of modern GPUs, they can also revise generated tokens, making them more suitable for revising existing text."

71
00:09:58,300 --> 00:10:07,087
The models are available as Open Models (3B, 8B, 14B text; 8B vision-language) via HuggingFace .

72
00:10:07,087 --> 00:10:20,675
Particularly relevant for teams optimizing inference costs or working on text-revision workflows — the ability to revise already-generated tokens is a genuine differentiator versus classical autoregressive models.

73
00:10:20,675 --> 00:10:23,612
Nemotron-Labs Diffusion on HuggingFace

74
00:10:23,612 --> 00:10:24,762
Fail of the Week.

75
00:10:24,762 --> 00:10:29,887
"$50M ARR — $42M of it actually active"

76
00:10:29,887 --> 00:10:46,150
A systemic problem runs through the AI startup scene: startups and their investors present "Contracted ARR" (CARR) as regular ARR — counting contracts not yet activated, free pilot phases, and multi-year deals as ongoing revenue .

77
00:10:46,150 --> 00:10:59,225
A concrete example from the report: one startup reported $50M ARR, but only $42M was active; another counted year-long free pilot phases as ARR — and the board knew it .

78
00:10:59,225 --> 00:11:02,787
"The biggest funds support this and mislead journalists."

79
00:11:02,787 --> 00:11:05,425
— Scott Stevenson, Spellbook CEO

80
00:11:05,425 --> 00:11:09,312
"Some investors look the other way when their companies inflate numbers."

81
00:11:09,312 --> 00:11:11,425
— Jack Newton, Clio CEO

82
00:11:11,425 --> 00:11:14,325
Root cause: Structural incentive conflict.

83
00:11:14,325 --> 00:11:20,362
VCs benefit from inflated paper valuations for easier fundraising and talent acquisition.

84
00:11:20,362 --> 00:11:26,562
Anyone who breaks the convention looks worse than competitors who play along — a classic race to the bottom .

85
00:11:26,562 --> 00:11:35,587
What we learn: When evaluating AI startups, always ask for the distinction between CARR (Contracted ARR) and active, paying ARR.

86
00:11:35,587 --> 00:11:38,812
Anyone who won't answer that question has something to hide.

